Two `.cpp` files both `#include "widget.h"`. The header is shown below. What problem will occur at link time?

```cpp
// widget.h  (no include guard)
class Widget {
public:
    int id;
    void show();
};

void Widget::show() {
    std::cout << id << '\n';
}
```

Assuming a single-file program (no separate `.h`), what does this print?

```cpp
#include <iostream>
class Temp {
public:
    int val;
    Temp(int v) : val{v} {}
    void show() const { std::cout << val * 2 << '\n'; }
};
int main() {
    Temp t{7};
    t.show();
}
```
